As mentioned above about ping sweep:
A ping sweep is a simple network discovery technique used to find which devices are alive (reachable) on a network.

What “ping sweep” means
You take a range of IP addresses (like 192.168.0.1–254)
Send a probe (ping or similar) to each one
Any device that responds is marked as “up”

👉 It’s basically:
“Who’s online in this network?”

Command using Nmap

With Nmap, the modern ping sweep command is:

nmap -sn 192.168.0.0/24
What this does
-sn → Host discovery only (no port scanning)
192.168.0.0/24 → Scans all 254 usable IPs in that subnet
What you’ll see

Example output:

Nmap scan report for 192.168.0.1
Host is up
Nmap scan report for 192.168.0.5
Host is up

→ These are the devices currently connected

Important detail (many people miss this)

A “ping sweep” doesn’t always use just ICMP ping.

Nmap may use:

ICMP echo (traditional ping)
ARP requests (on local networks)
TCP probes (like SYN to port 443)

This makes it more reliable than basic ping.

Alternative (old command)
nmap -sP 192.168.0.0/24
Same thing, but deprecated
Use -sn instead
Simple analogy


