The -Pn option in Nmap changes how Nmap treats the target before scanning.

What nmap -Pn <ip> means
-Pn = “No ping”
It tells Nmap:
👉 “Don’t check if the host is up, just assume it is and scan it anyway.”

+++++++++++++++++++
Why this matters

Normally, Nmap does this first:

Sends a ping / host discovery probe
If the host doesn’t respond → Nmap assumes it’s down and skips it

With -Pn:

Nmap skips that check completely
It goes straight into port scanning

+++++++++++++++++++

When you use it

Use -Pn when:
You know the host the up
A device is blocking ping/ICMP
You suspect a firewall is hiding the host

Nmap says:

Host seems down

but you know it’s actually up

+++++++++++++++++++

Example
nmap -Pn 192.168.0.122

Even if the device ignores ping:

Nmap will still try ports like 80, 443, 22, etc.
Trade-offs
🐢 Slower → because it scans even dead hosts
🔍 More reliable in restricted networks
⚠️ Can waste time if many IPs are actually offline

